<h2 id="B">Problem Set B</h2>
<ol type="1">
<li><p>There are 63 piles of bananas with <span class="math inline">\(n\)</span> bananas each, and 7 additional bananas. All of these bananas are divided evenly among 23 travelers. How many bananas can be in each pile? (Describe the set of all possible values of <span class="math inline">\(n\)</span>.)</p>
<p><em>Note</em>. This is a slight variant on a problem posed by the ninth-century mathematician <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mah%C4%81v%C4%ABra_(mathematician)">MahƒÅvƒ´ra</a>.</p></li>
<li><p>Prove that <span class="math inline">\(n!+1\)</span> and <span class="math inline">\((n+1)!+1\)</span> are relatively prime for any integer <span class="math inline">\(n \geq 1\)</span>.</p></li>
<li><p>Prove that <span class="math display">\[ \frac{\gcd(m,n)}{n} \binom{n}{m} \]</span> is an integer for all integers <span class="math inline">\(n \geq m \geq 1\)</span>.</p>
<p><em>Possible hint</em>. Write <span class="math inline">\(\gcd(m,n)\)</span> as a linear combination of <span class="math inline">\(m\)</span> and <span class="math inline">\(n\)</span>.</p></li>
<li><p>Loki has acquired a well-earned reputation as a mischief-maker among the gods of Asgard. One day, Loki steals the goddess I√∞unn‚Äôs apples of eternal youth. With a wide grin on his face, he tells I√∞unn that he‚Äôs thinking of a perfect square which has remainder 3 when divided by 7, and if she tells him what number he‚Äôs thinking of, he‚Äôll return her apples. I√∞unn thinks about this for a few minutes, and then says ‚Äú‚Ä¶‚Äù Loki glumly returns her apples. What does I√∞unn say?</p></li>
<li><p>Define a sequence of integers recursively by declaring <span class="math inline">\(S_1 = 1\)</span>, <span class="math inline">\(S_2 = 2\)</span>, and <span class="math display">\[ S_{n+2} = 2S_{n+1} + S_n \]</span> for all <span class="math inline">\(n \geq 1\)</span>. How many divisions must the Euclidean algorithm perform when computing <span class="math inline">\(\gcd(S_{n+1}, S_n)\)</span> before it finds a remainder of 0? What is this gcd? How would your answers to these questions change if the initial conditions used to define the sequence were <span class="math inline">\(S_1 = 14\)</span> and <span class="math inline">\(S_2 = 49\)</span> instead?</p></li>
<li><p>Recall the definition of the <em>triangular numbers</em> <span class="math inline">\(t_n\)</span> from section 2.1, problem 1. Give an explicit description of the set of all positive integers <span class="math inline">\(n\)</span> such that <span class="math inline">\(n \mid (t_1 + \dotsb + t_n)\)</span>.</p>
<p><em>Possible hint</em>. You may find it helpful to use results you‚Äôve proved on comprehension checks. If you do this, make sure to TeX up your proofs to these results as a part of your solution to this problem.</p></li>
